
CHAPTER VIII.

SUMMER drew to an end, and early Autumn--
it was past Michaelmas, but the harvest was late
that year, and a few of our fields were still un-
cleared.

Mr. Linton and his daughter would fre-
quently walk out among the reapers: at the
carrying of the last sheaves, they stayed till
dusk, and the evening happening to be chill
and damp, my master caught a bad cold, that
settling obstinately on his lungs, confined him
